===Etymology 2===
Representing various noun-suffixes in Old French and Anglo-Norman, variously ''-er'', ''-ier'' and ''-ieür'', from Latin [[-aris]], [[-arius]], [[-atorium]].

====Suffix====
'''-er''' ''(no longer productive)''

# Forming nouns from Old French and Anglo-Norman, usually with sense of ‘person or thing connected with’
#:''danger'', ''butler''

===Etymology 3===
Old English [[-ra]] (''masculine''), [[-re]] (''feminine, neuter''), [[-or]] (''adverbial''), from Germanic.

====Suffix====
'''-er''' ''(productive)''

#Used to form the {{compar}} of certain [[adjective]]s and [[adverb]]s, now especially short ones.
#:''longer'', ''bigger'', ''faster'', ''sooner'', ''simpler''

=====Usage notes=====
#Final ''y'' becomes ''i'' when this suffix is added ('''easy''', '''easier'''; '''worry''', '''worrier''').
#This suffix may be used to form the comparative of:
#:*adjectives and adverbs that have one syllable('''hot''', '''hotter'''; '''fast''', '''faster''');
#:*some, but not all, adjectives that have two syllables ('''funny''', '''funnier''').
#Most longer adjectives, and adjectives that are participles, form the comparative using '''more''' ('''enormous''', '''more enormous'''; '''burnt''', '''more burnt'''; '''freezing''', '''more freezing''').
#If in doubt, use '''more''' instead ('''thirsty''' may become '''thirstier''' but '''more thirsty''' would also be acceptable).

=====Translations=====
{{top}}
*French: [[plus#French|plus]] (''used before the adjective or adverb'')
*German: '''-er'''
*Italian: [[più]] (''used before the adjective or adverb'')
{{mid}}
*Spanish: [[más]] (''used before the adjective or adverb'')
*Swedish: [[mer]] (''used before the adjective or adverb''), [[-are]]
{{bottom}}

===Etymology 4===
Representing Anglo-Norman ''-er'', the infinitive verbal ending.

====Suffix====
'''-er''' ''(no longer productive)''

# Forming nouns from verbs with the sense of ‘instance of the verbal action’, especially in legal terms
#:''disclaimer'', ''misnomer''

===Etymology 5===
Old English [[-erian]], [[-rian]], from Germanic.

====Suffix====
'''-er'''

# Forming frequentative verbs from verbs or imitative sounds.
#:''twitter'', ''clamber'', ''mutter''

===Etymology 6===
Originally Rugby School slang.

====Suffix====
'''-er'''

# Forming slang or colloquial equivalents of words.
#:''soccer'', ''rugger''

